  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) establishment in 1989\n- Basel Committee recommendations\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n- Development of comprehensive regulatory frameworks\n\n3. Regulatory Requirements\n- Customer due diligence procedures\n- Mandatory transaction reporting\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Enhanced electronic monitoring systems\n\n4. Global Compliance Standards\n- International standardization of anti-money laundering protocols\n- Regular updates to legal frameworks\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Cross-border information sharing mechanisms\n\n5. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing cryptocurrency transactions\n- Digital platform monitoring\n- Advanced data analytics for detecting suspicious activities\n- Machine learning and AI-powered detection systems\n\n6. Recent Trends\n- Stricter beneficial ownership transparency requirements\n- Expanded scope of regulated financial institutions\n- Enhanced sanctions enforcement\n- More comprehensive risk-based approaches\n\nThese developments reflect growing sophistication in preventing financial crimes.",
